href=\"https://github.com/terser/terser/blob/master/CHANGELOG.md\">terser's changelog</a>.</em></p>\n<blockquote>\n<h2>v5.6.1</h2>\n<ul>\n<li>Mark assignments to the <code>.prototype</code> of a class as pure</li>\n<li>Parenthesize <code>await</code> on the left of <code>**</code> (while accepting legacy non-parenthesised input)</li>\n<li>Avoided outputting NUL bytes in optimized RegExps, to stop the output from breaking other tools</li>\n<li>Added <code>exports</code> to domprops (<a href=\"https://github-redirect.dependabot.com/terser/terser/issues/939\">#939</a>)</li>\n<li>Fixed a crash when spreading <code>...this</code></li>\n<li>Fixed the computed size of arrow functions, which improves their inlining</li>\n</ul>\n<h2>v5.6.0</h2>\n<ul>\n<li>Added top-level await</li>\n<li>Beautify option has been removed in <a href=\"https://github-redirect.dependabot.com/terser/terser/issues/895\">#895</a></li>\n<li>Private properties, getters and setters have been added in <a href=\"https://github-redirect.dependabot.com/terser/terser/issues/913\">#913</a> and some more commits</li>\n<li>Docs improvements: <a href=\"https://github-redirect.dependabot.com/terser/terser/issues/896\">#896</a>, <a href=\"https://github-redirect.dependabot.com/terser/terser/issues/903\">#903</a>, <a href=\"https://github-redirect.dependabot.com/terser/terser/issues/916\">#916</a></li>\n</ul>\n<h2>v5.5.1</h2>\n<ul>\n<li>Fixed object properties with unicode surrogates on safari.</li>\n</ul>\n<h2>v5.5.0</h2>\n<ul>\n<li>Fixed crash when inlining uninitialized variable into template string.</li>\n<li>The sourcemap for dist was removed for being too large.</li>\n</ul>\n<h2>v5.4.0</h2>\n<ul>\n<li>Logical assignment</li>\n<li>Change <code>let x = undefined</code> to just <code>let x</code></li>\n<li>Removed some optimizations for template strings, placing them behind <code>unsafe</code> options. Reason: adding strings is not equivalent to template strings, due to valueOf differences.</li>\n<li>The AST_Token class was slimmed down in order to use less memory.</li>\n</ul>\n<h2>v5.3.8</h2>\n<ul>\n<li>Restore node 13 support</li>\n</ul>\n<h2>v5.3.7</h2>\n<p>Hotfix release, fixes package.json &quot;engines&quot; syntax</p>\n<h2>v5.3.6</h2>\n<ul>\n<li>Fixed parentheses when outputting <code>??</code> mixed with <code>||</code> and <code>&amp;&amp;</code></li>\n<li>Improved hygiene of the symbol generator</li>\n</ul>\n<h2>v5.3.5</h2>\n<ul>\n<li>Avoid moving named functions into default exports.</li>\n<li>Enabled transform() for chain expressions. This allows AST transformers to reach inside chain expressions.</li>\n</ul>\n<!-- raw HTML omitted -->\n</blockquote>\n<p>... You can achieve the same result by closing it manually\n- `@dependabot ignore this major version` will close this PR and stop Dependabot creating any more for this major version (unless you reopen the PR or upgrade to it yourself)\n- `@dependabot ignore this minor version` will close this PR and stop Dependabot creating any more for this minor version (unless you reopen the PR or upgrade to it yourself)\n- `@dependabot ignore this dependency` will close this PR and stop Dependabot creating any more for this dependency (unless you reopen the PR or upgrade to it yourself)\n\n\n</details>",

      "type": "User",
      "site_admin": false
    },
    "body": "Resolves #32372, resolves #31646\r\n\r\nThis points out that components that transition may have a blind spot in testing. Since transition duration & delay is computed using [getTransitionDurationFromElement(element)](https://github.com/twbs/bootstrap/blob/main/js/src/util/index.js#L76), which gets transitions from css, its always going to be returning 0 in the unit tests unless otherwise mocked or styled inline. That means that any components that use this transition method will have tests that mostly ignore them... which may not actually matter (likely true), but at least in this case it does matter.\r\n\r\nIdeal in testing you'd mock the actual `getTransitionDurationFromElement(element)` imo, and just return the duration, however I was having some trouble getting jasmine spys to properly do this. I went for the next best thing in this case, which is mocking computed styles to get a non-zero return from that function. Happy to change it if anyones got ideas.\r\n\r\nPreview: https://deploy-preview-33289--twbs-bootstrap.netlify.app/docs/5.0/components/tooltips/",

    "body": "Closes #33181\r\n\r\nSince this option is not working already, dropping it should not be a breaking change IMO.\r\n\r\nNot adding the `fallbackPlacements` here in place of the `flip` option because the Popper's default value for this option is not customized by Bootstrap. Bootstrap is not customizing the value for `fallbackPlacements` because it is not needed: #32843. Users can change the flipping behavior by passing the array in the `fallbackPlacements` option directly in Popper's config. (For example, flipping behavior can be disabled by passing an empty array to the `fallbackPlacements` option.)",

    "body": "Follow-up PR of #33136 for Bootstrap 4.\r\n\r\nThis also removes the global modifier from the `SAFE_URL_PATTERN` regex, see the other PR for details why.\r\n\r\nSince Bootstrap V4 uses a different unit testing strategy than V5, based on the `dist` files, the sanitizer is not directly accessible since the file is inlined into `tooltip.js`. Therefore, the unit test for the sanitation has been added to the tooltip unit tests and simply adds two tooltips with the same HTML template to the test fixture. Then it checks that the tooltips contents are correct, using the same logic as the unit test in V5.\r\n\r\nI verified that the test works by first running it with the global modifier on the regex, where it fails, then removing the global modifier and it passes.",

    "body": "Recently, the method used to check attributes in the sanitizer has been switched from `match` to `test`.\r\n\r\nThe `test` method on regexes however behaves different than the `match` method on strings in the presence of the global modifier (g).\r\nSee [here](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Global_Objects/RegExp/test) for an example where the same input returns true, then false.\r\n\r\nThis modifier causes issues when the same template is sanitized multiple times, which happens when hovering over tooltips containing an `<img src>` tag for example.\r\n\r\nThis PR also adds a unit test for sanitizing the same template twice.\r\n\r\nThis fixes #33124.",

href=\"https://katiek2.github.io/path-doc/\">add it to your PATH</a>, or see <a href=\"https://sass-lang.com/install\">the Sass website</a> for full installation instructions.</p>\n<h1>Changes</h1>\n<ul>\n<li>\n<p>Allow the null safety release of stream_transform.</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p>Allow <code>@forward...with</code> to take arguments that have a <code>!default</code> flag without   a trailing comma.</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p>Improve the performance of unitless and single-unit numbers.</p>\n</li>\n</ul>\n<p>See the <a href=\"https://github.com/sass/dart-sass/blob/master/CHANGELOG.md#1327\">full changelog</a> for changes in earlier have a <code>!default</code> flag without\na trailing comma.</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p>Improve the performance of unitless and single-unit     "body": "Bumps [terser](https://github.com/terser/terser) from 5.1.0 to 5.6.0.\n<details>\n<summary>Changelog</summary>\n<p><em>Sourced from <a href=\"https://github.com/terser/terser/blob/master/CHANGELOG.md\">terser's changelog</a>.</em></p>\n<blockquote>\n<h1>Changelog</h1>\n<h2>v5.5.1</h2>\n<ul>\n<li>Fixed object properties with unicode surrogates on safari.</li>\n</ul>\n<h2>v5.5.0</h2>\n<ul>\n<li>Fixed crash when inlining uninitialized variable into template string.</li>\n<li>The sourcemap for dist was removed for being too large.</li>\n</ul>\n<h2>v5.4.0</h2>\n<ul>\n<li>Logical assignment</li>\n<li>Change <code>let x = undefined</code> to just <code>let x</code></li>\n<li>Removed some optimizations for template strings, placing them behind <code>unsafe</code> options. Reason: adding strings is not equivalent to template strings, due to valueOf differences.</li>\n<li>The AST_Token class was slimmed down in order to use less memory.</li>\n</ul>\n<h2>v5.3.8</h2>\n<ul>\n<li>Restore node 13 support</li>\n</ul>\n<h2>v5.3.7</h2>\n<p>Hotfix release, fixes package.json &quot;engines&quot; syntax</p>\n<h2>v5.3.6</h2>\n<ul>\n<li>Fixed parentheses when outputting <code>??</code> mixed with <code>||</code> and <code>&amp;&amp;</code></li>\n<li>Improved hygiene of the symbol generator</li>\n</ul>\n<h2>v5.3.5</h2>\n<ul>\n<li>Avoid moving named functions into default exports.</li>\n<li>Enabled transform() for chain expressions. This allows AST transformers to reach inside chain expressions.</li>\n</ul>\n<h2>v5.3.4</h2>\n<ul>\n<li>Fixed a crash when hoisting (with <code>hoist_vars</code>) a destructuring variable declaration</li>\n</ul>\n<h2>v5.3.3</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><code>source-map</code> library has been updated, bringing memory usage and CPU time improvements when reading input source maps (the SourceMapConsumer is now WASM based).</li>\n<li>The <code>wrap_func_args</code> option now also wraps arrow functions, as opposed to only function expressions.</li>\n</ul>\n<h2>v5.3.2</h2>\n<ul>\n<li>Prevented spread operations from being expanded when the expanded array/object contains getters, setters, or array holes.</li>\n<li>Fixed <em>very</em> slow self-recursion in some cases of removing extraneous parentheses from <code>+</code> operations.</li>\n</ul>\n<!-- raw HTML omitted -->\n</blockquote>\n<p>... (truncated)</p>\n</details>\n<details>\n<summary>Commits</summary>\n<ul>\n<li>See full diff in <a href=\"https://github.com/terser/terser/commits\">compare view</a></li>\n</ul>\n</details>\n<br />\n\n\n[![Dependabot compatibility score](https://dependabot-badges.githubapp.com/badges/compatibility_score?dependency-name=terser&package-manager=npm_and_yarn&previous-version=5.1.0&new-version=5.6.0)](https://docs.github.com/en/github/managing-security-vulnerabilities/about-dependabot-security-updates#about-compatibility-scores)\n\nYou can trigger a rebase of this PR by commenting `@dependabot rebase`.\n\n[//]: # (dependabot-automerge-start)\n[//]: # (dependabot-automerge-end)\n\n---\n\n<details>\n<summary>Dependabot commands and options</summary>\n<br />\n\nYou can trigger Dependabot actions by commenting on this PR:\n- `@dependabot rebase` will rebase this PR\n- `@dependabot recreate` will recreate this PR, overwriting any edits that have been made to it\n- `@dependabot merge` will merge this PR after your CI passes on it\n- `@dependabot squash and merge` will squash and merge this PR after your CI passes on it\n- `@dependabot cancel merge` will cancel a previously requested merge and block automerging\n- `@dependabot reopen` will reopen this PR if it is closed\n- `@dependabot close` will close this PR and stop Dependabot recreating it.     "body": "Fixes #26202, closes #32244.\r\n\r\nOriginally mentioned by me at https://github.com/twbs/bootstrap/pull/32244#issuecomment-760444399.\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\nUses generated content via CSS to add the numbers inside list group items. This is done because the styling available for normal ordered/numbered lists affords basically no ability to style, place, align, etc the numbers. This way, people can apply their own custom styles to the `::before` element and match or differentiate them as desired.\r\n\r\nPreview: https://deploy-preview-33068--twbs-bootstrap.netlify.app/docs/5.0/components/list-group/#ordered-list\r\n",

    "body": "I have added an additional variable to allow users to customise the value of the `blur` property for `box-shadows`. Previously, input shadows set their own blur value, which made it difficult to overwrite due to the usage of mixins to generate a lot of the validation styles; [Issue #31940](https://github.com/twbs/bootstrap/issues/31940).\r\n\r\nThis PR offers a new `$input-btn-focus-blur` variable, which defaults to a value of `0`, and is then used to populate the blur for all input related `box-shadow` variables.",

      "type": "User",
      "site_admin": false
    },
    "body": "It's unclear what the reason for first introducing the original hack here (for `[tabindex=\"-1\"]:focus {...}`) was. Seems something that may have been useful/necessary in SuitCSS, but don't think BS ever relied on this. https://github.com/twbs/bootstrap/issues/18330\r\nIt's since been modified to only apply when the browser wouldn't apply a visible outline anyway based on its own heuristics (the `:not(:focus-visible)` part) https://github.com/twbs/bootstrap/pull/28437/\r\n\r\nBut now, thinking this through more...in browsers that do support this pseudo-selector, what this is essentially saying is redundant: don't apply outline in cases where a `tabindex=\"-1\"` element receives focus but the browser wouldn't normally apply focus outline\". at best, this is unnecessary. at worst, this actually overrides things an author may explicitly be trying to do with adding `:focus { outline: ... }` explicitly.",

    "body": "Our current trick works great for headings or landmarks `:target`ed by links activation, however it still allows focus to be hidden under the sticky header. \r\n\r\n1. Go to any docs page, \r\n2. use a TOC link to scroll down the page, \r\n3. then `Shift`+`Tab` to navigate backward using keyboard. \r\n\r\nYou should see on some browsers (mainly Firefox from my tests, but it used to do the same in Chrome) that focused elements isn't visible, hidden by our sticky header.\r\n\r\nApplying `scroll-padding-top` to the `:root` solves this without any side-effectbut it requires to drop `scroll-margin-top` for anchors to prevent doubling the offset.\r\n\r\nFWIW based on my test, Edgium and Chromium don't really care since they seem to have a new heuristic for such cases, making the focused element scroll to the center of the view.\r\n\r\nFriendly ping @mdo @patrickhlauke if you have any concerns or insights on this.",

      "type": "User",
      "site_admin": true
    },
    "body": "This does a couple things in an attempt to resolve, at least temporarily, our dropdown menu alignment issues.\r\n\r\n1. Removes the `&[style] { ... }` override @MartijnCuppens added. This alone resolves #32484, but this caused other issues with the  menu alignment classes on static dropdowns.\r\n\r\n2. So, to fix that, now the menu alignment classes `.dropdown-menu-start` and `.dropdown-menu-end` are positioned via Popper and use the `--bs-position` CSS variable. I've removed the `left` and `right` properties for those.\r\n\r\n3. And, in combination, I've scoped those `left` and `right` properties to instances of the `-start` and `-end` classes that are used with `data-bs-display=\"static\"`. It's not the best, but it resolves the alignment near as I can tell for all dropdown menus, static or otherwise.\r\n\r\nIn the docs, I've added a temporary set of all the dropdown alignment options at the top of the page so I can quickly check things. I'll migrate this to the cheatsheet pages I think before merging, but didn't want to do that until getting some eyes on this.\r\n\r\nWhatcha thinkgood enough for solving our woes ahead of Beta 2?\r\n\r\n/cc @ffoodd @XhmikosR \r\n\r\nTODO:\r\n\r\n- [x] clean up squash any patches manually\r\n- [x] needs tests",

    "body": "This pull request seeks to offer the beginnings of a solution to issue #27514.\r\n\r\nFollowing a conversation with @mdo (and @ffoodd) on his personal [AMA]( https://github.com/mdo/ama/issues/300) I decided to attempt to merge my experimentations with Dark Mode in my [bootstrap-dark-5]( https://github.com/vinorodrigues/bootstrap-dark-5) project, that in turn was just an add on to my [bootstrap-dark]( https://github.com/vinorodrigues/bootstrap-dark) ramblings.\r\n\r\nThis submission is a very specific iteration of those works wherein I attempt to merge a pure `prefers-color-scheme: dark` media query driven Dark Mode as a 5th variant of the CSS.  That means no toggle button etc., but easily attainable with one line setting in the `_variables.scss` file and a whole lot of JS to drive that. *(I can contribute to building that a bit later.)*\r\n\r\nThis work, and the original works, would not have been possible without the advice of Thomas Steiner (@tomayac) and his [prefers-color-scheme: Hello darkness, my old friend](https://web.dev/prefers-color-scheme/) blog post.  Reading that (and his [color-scheme CSS property](https://web.dev/color-scheme/) post) and some of @mdos work inspired the original text.\r\n\r\nIt includes both the SCSS changes and the docs to go along with it.",

    "body": "Since shallow merge is used to merge `popperConfig` passed by the user for popper's config, this overrides the `modifiers` property instead of merging the array.\r\n\r\nSo creating `popperConfig` a function and then passing the default configuration as an argument gives users the ability to use the default configuration and merge it with their configuration. Keeping the previous type `object` in the supported types since removing it would be a breaking change.\r\n\r\nRef: https://github.com/twbs/bootstrap/pull/32443#issuecomment-748806985\r\n\r\n@XhmikosR Let me know if it is a good idea :slightly_smiling_face: ",
